<TEXT>
two inmates apparently escaped monday night from 
the federal prison where manuel noriega is being held pending his 
drug trial police said 
the deposed panamanian leader wasnt involved 
the two inmates were seen scaling a fence on the extensive 
grounds of the federal metropolitan correctional center south of 
miami said prison spokesman charles davis but it was unclear if 
the men actually got beyond the outer fence he said 
our perimiter patrolman fired on the inmates and claims he hit 
one on the shoulder davis said they may have gotten out of 
the perimiter of the property 
police believed they may have gotten into a large public park 
nearby 
police identified the prisoners as omar fernandez a convicted 
bank robber and charles carew who is serving time for cocaine 
possession 
at least three helicopters squadrons of police officers and 
police dogs surrounded the prison 
police checked every car leaving the prison grounds and at least 
one us customs helicopter fitted with infrared lights for night 
vision hovered over the area 
guards searched inside the prison grounds but the most of the 
search concentrated outside the fence 
many of the inmates are allowed relative freedom inside the 
wooded 48acre compound southwest of miami but noriega is under 
constant watch by a guard posted outside his specially built cell 
in the administration building 
the mediumsecurity mcc was designed to hold 425 inmates between 
trips to the federal courthouse in miami about 25 miles away now 
more than 1100 live there sleeping two to a cell taxing the 
ability of guards to watch over them about 700 of the inmates are 
in pretrial detention 300 were returned from prisons outside 
florida to await trials here and about 100 inmates are serving full 
sentences 
security was tightened after barry kramer a former powerboat 
racing champion serving life without parole for leading a drug 
trafficking ring arranged for a friend to pick him up by 
helicopter in april 
the copter crashed into the fence surrounding an exercise yard 
injuring both the wouldbe escapee and the pilot 
three successful escapes have occurred since 1981 davis said 
once a prisoner walked out the front door with visitors made up 
in lipstick and dressed in his wifes clothes 
another inmate slipped out by hanging onto the undercarriage of 
a dade county bookmobile he was captured two years later 
the third rode out in a trash bin and narrowly escaped being 
compacted 
