japan and the soviet union hold toplevel talks 
this week amid growing willingness on both sides to improve 
relations even if a stubborn 45yearold land dispute remains 
unresolved 
soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze arrives tuesday for 
talks with his japanese counterpart and japanese prime minister 
toshiki kaifu 
moscows ties with japan have not kept pace with its improving 
relations with western countries this is because of continuing 
bitterness over a group of small islands off northern japan seized 
by soviet troops in the final days of world war ii 
for years japan has demanded that the islands be returned the 
two countries never formally signed a treaty ending world war ii 
hostilities as a result of the dispute 
