<TEXT>
nasas third countdown for the space 
shuttle columbia and its astronomy mission proceeded uninterrupted 
monday as the space agency aimed for a thursday liftoff 
we want the shuttle columbia and the science payload to be 
right when we launch said vance brand commander of the 
sevenman crew we are enthusiastic about the mission and ready 
to fly it 
the latest countdown began early monday and liftoff is scheduled 
for 120 am edt thursday if the columbia takes off it will be 
the first shuttle launched since hydrogen fuel leaks grounded 
nasas threeshuttle fleet in the spring 
columbia originally was scheduled to lift off with the 150 
million astro observatory in march 1986 however the january 1986 
explosion of the challenger which killed all seven crew members 
postponed all shuttle missions 
columbias launch was eventually rescheduled for may 30 of this 
year but hydrogen fuel leaks halted the countdown 
a month later the atlantis shuttle also was found to have 
hydrogen leaks prompting the national aeronautics and space 
administration to ground the whole fleet atlantis classified 
pentagon mission originally scheduled for july is now set for 
november 
last week communications problems with astros xray telescope 
halted columbias second countdown the launch had been scheduled 
for saturday 
four astronomers on board will take turns operating astros 
three ultraviolet telescopes round the clock but the xray 
telescope has to be managed by computer commands sent from goddard 
space flight center in greenbelt md 
the communication problem was corrected over the weekend when 
workers replaced an electronic component in the 1500pound xray 
telescope anchored along with the ultraviolet telescopes in 
columbias cargo bay a minor software problem was fixed sunday 
the columbia would be the first shuttle launched since april 
when discovery carried the flawed hubble space telescope into 
orbit the stretch between missions is the longest since flights 
resumed in 1988 following the challenger disaster 
a beleaguered nasa has spent the summer also contending with 
hubbles defective mirror and communications problems with the 
venusorbiting magellan spacecraft 
at nasas jet propulsion laboratory in california engineers 
hoped computer commands radioed this week and next would restore 
the magellan spacecraft to normal operation they have not 
determined why the magellan suffered two long communications 
blackouts but hoped its 744 million mission to map venus with 
radar would begin this month 
weve had some trouble but responding to trouble fixing 
problems is our strong suit said columbia test director mike 
leinbach weve been disappointed several times of course but 
thursday morning we hope thats all behind us 
im ready to get this one off the ground and move on to 
discoverys planned flight in october with the ulysses spacecraft 
leinbach said ulysses is to study the sun 
columbias nine to 10day mission will be one of the longest 
since the first shuttle flight in 1981 it also will be the first 
shuttle mission in five years devoted entirely to scientific 
research 
astro will examine some of the hottest objects in the universe 
including a supernova and comet levy which is making its first 
recorded pass through the solar system the observatory will remain 
in the cargo bay and be returned to earth for possible use on a 
future mission 
</TEXT>
