<TEXT>
labor day weekend 1990 a time to spend 
with family and friends maybe go to beach or maybe a time to 
march in the blazing sun wearing your m17a2 gas mask and 
charcoallined chemical warfare suit 
then if theres time before dinner you can practice what to do 
in case of nuclear attack 
so goes the holiday weekend for the 265th quartermaster 
detachment 14 south carolina guardsmen training for deployment to 
the persian gulf 
the water purification unit was placed on active duty a week 
ago the men all from the small community of allendale sc have 
been at fort stewart since thursday brushing up on survival skills 
they did not take the holiday off they jogged before dawn to 
prepare civilian bodies for possible military action overseas they 
devoted part of the afternoon to throwing themselves on the ground 
in the prescribed method of surviving a nuclear explosion 
most of the day was spent outside the barracks in 90degree 
heat practicing how to survive chemical warfare 
over and over a timekeeper would shout gas and the men 
in the posture of old west gunfighters clawed at the gas mask bags 
hanging on their hips trying to get them over their heads before 
nine seconds passed and the timekeeper yelled stop 
the unit would freeze and sgt bill bostick a vietnam veteran 
would inspect each man and declare him either dead or alive 
as crows called from the high pines the unit struggled into 
heavy olive drab chemical warfare jackets and pants then the 
thick black rubber gloves and overboots that keep out dangerous 
chemicals but keep in all body heat 
the unit marched in single file past the rows of cinder block 
barracks where other reservists sat listening to rap music after 
the walk sweat dripped steadily from the bottom of their masks it 
poured from the gloves when the men pulled them off 
if we have to spend too much time in these suits over there 
where its 120 degrees theres going to be a lot of dead boys from 
allendale spc edward simmons a lumber truck driver said 
goodnaturedly 
