<TEXT>
while the middle east crisis will occupy 
center stage when president bush meets with mikhail gorbachev next 
sunday the soviet leader certainly could be forgiven if he also 
tries to steer the conversation around to his own economys 
desperate situation 
gorbachev has been struggling with a myriad of economic problems 
in recent weeks ranging from a continued shortage of consumer goods 
on store shelves to wrangling among competing economic commissions 
over just how fast the soviet economy should move to a freemarket 
system 
gorbachev is appealing for massive financial aid to turn the 
situation around but the united states and many of its allies are 
demanding a look at the soviet balance sheets before they commit to 
any major assistance programs 
many analysts believe those studies especially one being 
conducted by the international monetary fund could prove critical 
in determining the fate of gorbachevs faltering economic reforms 
in announcing the hastily scheduled summit in helsinki finland 
the white house on saturday said it would focus primarily on the 
middle east but bush said the discussions would not be limited to 
that area 
whatever the agenda the summit will allow gorbachev to turn 
briefly to statesmanship and away from his economic problems 
at the last meeting between the two leaders may 30june 3 in 
washington gorbachev stressed the need for western aid to insure 
the success of his efforts to rescue the faltering soviet economy 
bush however has remained opposed to direct soviet aid and 
even the ussoviet trade agreement which the two leaders did sign 
remains stalled awaiting passage in the soviet parliament of 
legislation to ensure free emigration 
the impasse is occurring as the soviet economy continues in a 
steep nose dive the total output of goods and services actually 
shrank during the first six months of the year while the countrys 
trade deficit has more than doubled and both unemployment and 
inflation are up sharply 
the soviet economy is disintegrating said marshall goldman 
the associate director of harvards russian research center 
everybody is standing around watching moscow burn but nobody 
knows what to do about it 
gorbachevs appeals for western aid will be considered this 
month when the imf and its sister organization the world bank 
hold their annual meetings in washington on sept 2027 
no decisions on those appeals are expected from the meetings 
but finance ministers from the 152 nations that make up the two 
organizations will discuss the imfled study which was ordered by 
president bush and other western leaders this summer at the 
economic summit of leading industrial nations in houston 
the study was a compromise between demands by the french and 
west germans for an immediate 15billion aid package and 
resistance to direct economic aid by bush and other summit leaders 
it is scheduled to be completed in december 
the international monetary fund generally is viewed as the top 
cop of international finance its clout stems not just from the 
loans it hands out but also from the fact that other lenders take 
their cue from the fund 
if for example the imf does not approve of a nations plans to 
get its economic house in order that nation has a hard time 
getting credit 
but imf austerity programs have in the past triggered bloody 
riots in third world nations unhappy with the prescription to curb 
runaway inflation 
whether the soviet union with its long history of distrust of 
western capitalism will readily accept imf dictates remains to be 
seen 
the study team faces other formidable obstacles 
there is the question of how to measure the soviet economy 
which operates with a currency that is not convertible into other 
foreign currencies 
while the central intelligence agency estimates that the soviet 
economy was roughly 51 percent the size of americas 42 trillion 
economy in 1989 other experts have attacked those figures as 
grossly inflated and suggested that the total output of soviet 
goods and services is really only onethird that of americas gross 
national product 
the imf study may resolve this debate since one of its main 
jobs will be to conduct an exhaustive look at a host of economic 
statistics these include soviet gross national product trade 
statistics and the amount of hard currency on hand to pay for 
shortfalls between what the country sells overseas and what it 
imports 
for decades the soviet union was considered a good 
international credit risk because the government always promptly 
paid its import bills but because of a widening trade gap the 
soviets have fallen behind on their payments and are seeking trade 
credits from other nations 
west germany already has agreed to 3 billion of such credits 
and other european nations are expected to follow suit 
the bush administration however has so far rejected proposals 
for direct financial aid and instead offered technical assistance 
including advice on improving the collapsing food distribution 
system or how to establish private banking 
but many experts believe that the soviet problems are so severe 
they can be resolved only by a major overhaul of the economy and 
massive economic support from the west 
the soviets face fundamental economic problems that are not 
amenable to quick fixes said jeffrey schott an expert at the 
institute for international economics a washingtonbased research 
organization the question of restructuring their entire economy 
and their distribution system will take quite a number of years to 
accomplish 
</TEXT>
