<TEXT>
as a young chicago architect in 1902 
frank lloyd wright got a dream job build a house with no limit on 
cost or creativity 
wright spent two years and 60000 planning every detail from 
walls to chairs now nearly nine decades later the state has 
spent three years and 5 million restoring the vision of the man 
who became americas most famous architect 
the result goes on display friday when the house wright designed 
for a wealthy widow opens to the public for the first time since 
1987 
this building is probably the most perfectly preserved of his 
early buildings said site manager donald hallmark literally 
almost everything he designed for it is still here 
the danathomas house named for its owners was one of 
wrights first large homes said wright expert elaine harrington 
curator at the wright home and studio foundation in oak park 
by 1902 the architect was growing in prominence but most of 
his work was still small homes in chicago suburbs 
the building is an example of the prairie style of 
architecture which emphasizes horizontal lines and an open 
flowing floor plan the twostory home looks vaguely like pagodas 
joined by a low walkway coppergreen rain gutters form a prominent 
border to the sloping roof a green plaster frieze runs near the 
top of the walls linking the roof to the pale brick below 
inside low dim rooms will suddenly give way to high ceilings 
and shafts of sunlight rooms seem connected at random with open 
spaces here and sudden turns there 
hallmark said architects usually have limited control over a 
homes furniture and decorations but wright designed everything 
like a composer writing music 
it is a long symphony hallmark said it is probably the 
greatest symphonic collection of decorative art objects that youre 
ever going to find from the early 20th century 
that collection of wright lamps stainedglass windows and 
furniture makes the danathomas house stand out experts say 
not all buildings are allowed to survive with all that 
intact harrington said if youre going to explain the work 
you need as much of that stuff as you can possibly afford 
gov james r thompson was a a chief supporter of the 
restoration the project spent 704000 in privately raised money 
to buy a lamp wright designed for the house the furniture is so 
valuable that its location was kept secret while it was being 
restored 
wright built the house for widow sarah lawrence dana to hold 
lavish parties poet carl sandburg sometimes read his work there 
and dana once held a reception for conductor john philip sousa she 
threw frequent parties one with 1000 guests 
eventually dana was hit with financial and health problems the 
thomas publishing co bought the house in 1944 using it as office 
space but also taking care to preserve the building as wright had 
designed it the house was sold to the state in 1981 for 1 
million a fraction of its value hallmark said 
