<TEXT>
cambodian guerrillas have moved at 
least 60000 refugees from camps in thailand back into cambodia and 
some have died from disease as a result western aid officials said 
today 
most of the refugees were from camps run by the communist khmer 
rouge said a senior aid official speaking on condition of 
anonymity the others were from a camp controlled by the allied 
guerrilla forces of prince norodom sihanouk 
he said the movements began after the september 1989 pullout of 
vietnamese troops from cambodia but most of the refugees had been 
relocated in the past six months they were moved apparently to 
consolidate areas the guerrillas recently liberated he said 
the relocations continue amid stepped up efforts to end the 
11year cambodian war 
the vietnameseinstalled phnom penh government has accepted an 
invitation to join the guerrillas in talks in jakarta indonesia 
on wednesday on an interim government and a new united nations 
peace plan 
its premier hun sen said in a statement broadcast on state 
radio sunday he hoped the meeting would open the way toward a 
common solution for the cambodian problem 
hun sen said he will attend if sihanouk the main guerrilla 
leader also attends otherwise the government will be represented 
by hor nam hong a minister in the prime ministers office in 
charge of foreign affairs 
the khmer rouge and the noncommunist sihanouk forces are allied 
with the khmer peoples national liberation front against hun sen 
the khmer rouge relocated millions during its brutal attempt in 
the 1970s to turn the country into a radical agrarian commune 
hundreds of thousands of people were executed or died of hunger and 
disease before vietnams late 1978 invasion ousted the fanatical 
regime 
the aid official said some refugees fell sick after the latest 
relocations and tried to return to unaided camps in thailand for 
treatment but some were prevented or delayed from doing so and had 
died mostly from malaria and anemia he said he said he could not 
give a figure 
you have people who are going voluntarily people who dont 
mind and people who are forced to go back he said 
our officers in the field believe the total number to be close 
to 100000 he said we believe we are facing a tremendous 
problem 
international relief officials have seen trucks taking the 
refugees to border crossing points said another aid official 
you can say that they died from a political decision that 
brought them back inside cambodia without providing them with the 
minimum of medical care he said 
as well as medical supplies we know there are shortages of 
food too although no one is starving yet he said 
in the past month some 1000 people had returned to the khmer 
rouge camp of site 8 with malaria tuberculosis and other diseases 
rife in the border region he said 
aid officials stressed they had an incomplete picture of the 
movements they said many refugees habitually cross the border and 
later return to the un camps in thailand they also raised the 
possibility the thai military had a hand in the movements 
there are more than 300000 refugees in camps along the thai 
border run by the guerrillas and given humanitarian aid by the un 
border relief operation 
however most of those moved by the khmer rouge were from their 
hidden satellite camps closed military and civilian 
communities near the un camps the khmer rouge and the thai 
military do not allow western aid agencies to work inside these 
camps but have let many refugees there seek medical assistance 
outside 
the senior relief official said the satellite camps near site 8 
the main unaided khmer rouge camp in prachinburi province and 
those farther south near the unaided site k camp in trat 
province were empty 
other movements were reported from areas along the northern part 
of the border near the un camp of otrao in sisaket province 
the refugees from the satellite camps near site 8 had to travel 
only a few miles to the border but those in the south had to walk 
for several days to reach their new homes where the medical 
situation was very bad the official said 
he said sihanouks authorities moved between 10000 and 20000 
people from site b a unaided camp along the northern border in 
surin province they were being moved mainly to two new settlements 
just across the border 
