<TEXT>
saudi arabia will boost its daily oil 
production by 227 million barrels this month to make up for the 
loss of iraqi and kuwaiti output the middle east economic survey 
reported today 
in addition the united arab emirates will boost output from 
fields in abu dhabi by about 450000 barrels a day the respected 
nicosiabased oil industry newsletter said 
before iraq invaded kuwait on aug 2 iraqs president saddam 
hussein warned that he would retaliate for the violation of opec 
quotas by kuwait and the uae the extra oil on markets was 
driving down crude prices 
a united nations economic embargo imposed on iraq four days 
after the invasion stopped iraqi and kuwaiti oil exports slashing 
available opec production by 4 million barrels a day and driving up 
prices 
the new increase in daily output follows an agreement by 
organization of petroleum exporting countries in vienna on aug 29 
to suspend quota restrictions and allow production to rise toward 
225 million barrels a day 
that was the production level set in geneva by the oil cartel on 
july 27 six days before iraq invaded kuwait 
the move to boost oil production by saudi arabia and the united 
arab emirates will boost saudi output to 765 million barrels 
daily and the emirates to about 2 million barrels a day 
the newsletter estimates that opec production will reach 221 
million barrels a day this month and rise to 231 million barrels 
daily by years end 
the vienna agreement was aimed at restoring market stability and 
salvaging opecs credibility in the wake of the persian gulf crisis 
the accord was seen as a major political victory for saudi 
arabia which had lobbied for a rapid production boost against 
opposition from other opec members notably iran the kingdom had 
threatened to boost production unilaterally if necessary 
the economic survey said saudi arabia will give priority to 
supplying developing countries whose oil supplies have been 
affected by the iraqkuwait cutoff 
these include turkey brazil the philippines india pakistan 
bangladesh taiwan and south korea 
next on the list are the japanese the newsletter said in last 
priority are increases for us and european buyers it said 
at the same time saudi arabia is also to supply crude on a 
commercial basis to two opec countries hit by the crisis the 
survey reported 
the kuwait petroleum co will be receiving 150000 barrels a 
day of saudi crude in september rising to 220000 barrels a day in 
october it said 
indonesia will be receiving saudi crude to make up for a 
30000 barreladay supply contract it had with iraq the 
newsletter reported 
the survey said 75 million barrels a day of the increased saudi 
production will come from aramco fields that is roughly the oil 
giants sustainable capacity although it has a shortterm surge 
capacity of up to 85 million barrels a day 
the rest of saudi arabias output will come from its half of the 
socalled neutral zone which it shares with kuwait 
the land fields in the zone whose production installations are 
on the kuwaiti side of the border have been closed since aug 2 
but the offshore fields which lie on the saudi arabian side 
remain in operation 
all the united arab emirates increase will come from abu dhabi 
the federations main producer dubai its other producer will 
maintain its current output of 400000 barrels a day the 
newsletter said 
whether abu dhabi production goes even higher in the fourth 
quarter will no doubt depend mainly on technical oilfield 
factors the newsletter noted 
venezuelan production is also expected to rise this month by 
350000 barrels a day increasing another 150000 barrels daily in 
november to a total of 500000 barrels a day 
newsletter editor ian seymour said the vienna accord stands a 
good chance of defusing the oil supply crisis in its present form 
that is to say unless anything worse happens in the middle east 
arena 
</TEXT>
