<TEXT>
upjohn co and other pharmaceutical 
firms are offering medicaid discounts as they try to preempt 
proposed legislation that would cap the cost of drugs sold to the 
poor 
last week kalamazoobased upjohn followed other industry 
leaders discount offers by proposing a 135 rebate for each 
medicaid prescription filled with its drugs 
i think its a smart move to try to eliminate the need for 
legislation said ronald nordmann an industry analyst with 
painewebber it probably wont mean much in terms of losses 
either since medicaid sales represent only about 10 percent of the 
market 
but theres a catch any state that accepts a companys discount 
must offer all of the companys drugs to medicaid patients even 
the expensive ones that some states now refuse thats expected to 
create virtual monopolies in some states by knocking competing 
drugs off reimbursement eligibility lists 
most of the largest drug companies have refused in the past to 
offer the same discounts to medicaid programs that they have given 
to the departments of defense and veterans affairs as well as 
hospitals and large health maintenance organizations 
but earlier this year the us health and human services 
department said it wanted to cut 1991 medicaid expenditures by 300 
million prompting a legislative proposal that would restrict the 
drugs covered by medicaid thereby forcing competitive bidding by 
drug companies 
sen david pryor dark who introduced the bill said it would 
save between 100 million and 200 million each year congressional 
hearings on the plan will be held in midseptember 
the cost of drugs sold to medicaid totals 35 billion a year 
at least 19 state medicaid programs have already limited the 
drugs they offer poor patients often excluding more expensive 
patented drugs as a way to get the drug companies to negotiate 
medicaid officials say drug prices are the fastest rising segment 
of their programs 
the pharmaceutical manufacturers association is adamantly 
opposed to legislation that would restrict access to any drug it 
says a federally mandated program for competitive bidding would 
lead to inferior health care for the poor 
under the bill manufacturers of chemically different drugs 
that treat the same disease would be required to bid against each 
other and the cheapest medicines which are almost always the 
oldest ones would win the bid association spokesman jeff 
trewhitt said friday 
medicaid patients would be deprived of some medicines and in 
many cases would be getting secondclass care 
trewhitt said many medical groups and advocacy groups for the 
poor are also opposed to the legislation the association has 
remained silent on the individual companies discount plans 
pryor chairman of the senate special committee on aging said 
last week that the current discount plans offered by merck amp co 
pfizer inc glaxo inc and upjohn arent good enough 
while i commend these four companies for offering national 
proposals the savings for medicaid and the safeguards to assure 
these savings are just not there pryor said 
