<TEXT>
when franklin d roosevelt told a nation mired in 
the depression that the only thing we have to fear is fear 
itself he was talking about the kind of economic fright that 
turns rumors into reality 
bank of new england got a taste of just what kind of damage 
false rumors can do in a nervous economic climate last week when 
talk hit wall street that federal regulators were preparing for a 
takeover 
area economists said massachusetts souring economy and the 
recent spate of federal bank takeovers nationwide have given 
rumors a potency they might not hold in better times 
i do think that the bad news sometimes can be cumulative and 
indeed feeds on itself said wayne ayers chief economist at the 
bank of boston 
james howell a former bank of boston economist who now runs his 
own consulting firm agreed that rumors thrive during a faltering 
economy 
when things begin to turn sour there is sort of a notion that 
i hope the bad things that are happening to other people wont 
happen to me therefore i respond to rumor as if some of it or 
all of it may be fact he said 
in the bank of new england flap a congressional candidate gave 
the rumor a substantial push democratic hopeful ted dimauro faxed 
a statement to news organizations lamenting the supposed federal 
takeover 
the bank has been struggling to recover from a downturn in the 
states economy especially from a decline in the real estate 
